 PM David Hildenbrand &lt;david&#64;redhat.com&gt; wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; If a page is mapped exactly once, page_mapcount(page) == 1 and there is<br />&gt; nothing to do.<br /><br />Why?<br /><br />You state that, but you stating that doesn't magically make it so.<br /><br />What makes "mapcount==1" stable and special? Your "it's an<br />atomic_read()" argument is nonsense - it implies that the count can be<br />changing, but you will get _one_ answer.<br /><br />What makes that one answer of a changing count special?<br /><br />What if there are other references to that same page, gotten with<br />vmsplice(), and just about to be mapped into another address space?<br /><br />This is the meat of my argument. You claim that "mapcount==1" is<br />special. I claim that you haven't explained why it would be. And I do<br />not believe it is.<br /><br />                 Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
